{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638423"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:53:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:53:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17707"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17707"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72021"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10421"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57491"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10409"},{"type":"tags","id":"10415"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24332"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24337"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72021"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETaste receptor cells in the taste buds of the tongue detect five basic taste qualities through different molecular mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of sweet taste signal transduction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activation of ligand-gated ion channels","Activation of G protein-coupled receptors","Direct diffusion through the cell membrane","Opening of proton-sensitive ion channels","Direct entry of sodium ions through ion channels"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESweet taste is detected through \u003Cstrong\u003Eactivation of G protein-coupled receptors\u003C/strong\u003E (T1R2/T1R3 heterodimers) on taste receptor cells. When sweet molecules bind to these receptors, they trigger a signalling cascade involving gustducin (G protein), leading to increased intracellular calcium and neurotransmitter release.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of ligand-gated ion channels\u003C/strong\u003E - While some sensory systems use this mechanism, sweet taste specifically requires G protein-coupled receptors for signal transduction.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect diffusion through the cell membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - Sweet molecules are too large and polar to cross cell membranes directly and require specific receptor-mediated detection.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpening of proton-sensitive ion channels\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism is specifically involved in sour taste detection where hydrogen ions directly activate specific ion channels.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect entry of sodium ions through ion channels\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents the mechanism for salty taste detection where sodium ions pass directly through specialised ion channels.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe G protein-coupled receptor mechanism allows for amplification of the sweet taste signal and is similar to the mechanism used for bitter and umami taste detection, though with different specific receptors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Taste receptor cells use G protein-coupled receptors to detect sweet, bitter and umami tastes.","Ion channels directly detect sour and salty tastes without second 